robot tests/smoke_tests.robot

Suppose you have:

File 1: tests/smoke_tests.robot

File 2: tests/regression_tests.robot

File 3: tests/api/critical_api.robot

robot tests/smoke_tests.robot tests/regression_tests.robot tests/api/critical_api.robot

This command executes every .robot test file inside the tests folder and its subdirectories at once.
robot tests/
If testcases in testsuite share a naming pattern Login then we can select them to execute
robot --suite "Login*" tests/regression_tests.robot

robot --tests "Login*" "goal settings*" newfile/goto/sample.robot

By tags: Assign tags to test cases, and run those with --include or -i:
robot --include smoke path/to/test_suite.robot
robot --include regression --include critical path/to/test_suite.robot

By name: Use a regex/wildcard in the --test option:
robot --test "Test [One|Two]" path/to/test_suite.robot

robot test1.robot test2.robot
robot *.robot

robot \
  --test "TC1 Login" \
  --test "TC3 Add Item" \
  --test "TC5 Checkout" \
  --test "TC7 Advanced Flow" \
  --test "TC9 Negative Scenario" \
  MySuite.robot

Run Keywords    Keyword From Suite1    AND    Keyword From Suite2

Split execution to suite files:

pabot [path to tests]

Split execution on test level:

pabot --testlevelsplit [path to tests]

Run with 8 parallel processes:

pabot --processes 8 [path to tests]
